{
  "project": "fixture-shop",
  "title": "Webhook HMAC Signature Verification",
  "slug": "webhook-hmac-signature-verification",
  "date": "2026-07-17",
  "depth": "intro",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "name": "HMAC Signature Verification",
      "definition": "A method of authenticating a message by recomputing a keyed hash (HMAC — Hash-based Message Authentication Code) over the message content using a shared secret, then comparing that computed hash against a hash provided by the sender. If the two match, the message both came from someone who knows the secret and was not altered in transit."
    },
    {
      "name": "Constant-Time Comparison",
      "definition": "A string comparison algorithm that always takes the same amount of time to execute regardless of how many characters match, preventing timing side-channel attacks where an attacker could deduce the correct value byte by byte by measuring how long a comparison takes."
    }
  ],
  "files": ["src/verify.php"],
  "commit": "f4daedf",
  "sources": [],
  "lesson": "The `verify()` function in `src/verify.php` decides whether an incoming webhook really came from the payment gateway. It recomputes an [[fixture-shop/_glossary#HMAC Signature Verification|HMAC-SHA256 signature]] over the raw request payload using the shared secret, then compares that against the signature header the sender provided. The comparison uses PHP's `hash_equals()`, a [[fixture-shop/_glossary#Constant-Time Comparison|constant-time comparison]], so an attacker cannot learn the correct signature byte by byte from response timing."
}

